<br>
There are crazy people on the net, and you've just walked into a club full of them. <p><a target="new" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=6094">Wenin Huirunda</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/urynnia.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Rynnia</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 752<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/31/02 11:06:00 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: In deference to the wheelchair bandit</span><hr size=1> I've never understood the whole concern over RL info being brought onto the pc.<br>
<br>
It forces the individual to act in a fashion they would act face to face, or at least thins the line between face to face and hiding behind a computer screen.<br>
<br>
People should be held accountable for their actions.  The whole anonymity of the internet sucks, in my opinion.  Many of the people who are assholes or spew forth shit at every turn would not do the same face to face.  They only do it because there is no consequence when they turn off that computer screen.  Every action should have a consequence for the individual that performs that action.  When consequences can be shut off with the press of a button or the pulling of a plug, you enter dangerous territory.  Stealing someone's mana robe is a minor example.  The concept spans a wide range of actions not only limited to EQ.<br>
<br>
Then again, some believe in a hard line between RL and &quot;on the computer&quot; as something that shouldn't be crossed.<br>
<br>
*shrug*<br>
<br>
Also, people need to stop calling RL names, addresses and phone numbers &quot;personal information.&quot;  It's all PUBLIC information.  Your name, address, and phone number will be sold, traded, and tossed around tens of thousands of times throughout your life.  Nothing you can do about that. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uarleanna.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arleanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>WERE YOU NOT<br>ENTERTAINED?!</span><br>  Posts: 539<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/31/02 12:30:53 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~jakecj7/EQ/Sphynx4.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: In deference to the wheelchair bandit</span><hr size=1> There are consequences to everything you do on the internet and in EQ. But those consequences should stay relative to the internet and EQ. <br>
<br>
If some person from AT&amp;T calls you every night getting you to switch to AT&amp;T long distance do you finally go bezerk, find her name and address and post them to every messageboard you can find? &quot;Hey everyone! This bitch is bothering me at home, let's all call her!&quot; As funny as that sounds I hope you can see that it is crossing the line.<br>
<br>
You go to a pickup soccor, hocky, or tag football game with some people you don't know at a local park. They tell you their first names but aren't about to let you know their life story. Well, your whole team is fucking around, pissing someone off, not playing by the rules, whatever... and the guy who owns one of the footballs flips out and says, &quot;Fuck this I'm taking my ball and going home&quot;. Do you think it's appropriate to follow him to his house then kick his ass? Then when every new person comes to play you tell them about this asshole you dont like and hand them a piece of paper with his phone number on it and encourage others to go pay him a visit? No, the appropriate consequence for that situation is just don't play with the guy anymore since you don't agree to play the game the same way.<br>
<br>
See Rynnia, you are one of those people who takes this game (and it is a game, you know) way too seriously. Your first reaction if someone wrongs you or doesn't play the game the same way you do is to look them up and find out where they live. That's seriously obsessive behavior man. And scarily enough there are even more fucked up people then you that play EQ and they would actually act on that real life information if it was posted somewhere.<br>
<br>
EQ IS NOT YOUR LIFE! Think of it as a pickup football game in the park. If someone steals your football, report them to the police or go pay them a visit yourself if it bothers you that much. But posting &quot;Soandso stole our football and this is where he lives!&quot; on a messageboard for other fucking retards to see is probably the most pussy thing I can think of doing.<br>
<br>
Even the police don't release personal info on convicted felons and for good reason. Sure that information may be available through public means, but there's a huge difference between publically available information and taking out a full page add in the New York Times because someone stole your pixels. If you can't see the difference Rynnia then there is something very wrong with how you view society and modern day sociological values.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
 <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=61467">Arleanna Mistmoore</a><BR>
<a href="http://www.The-Elitists.com">The Elitists and Vagrants</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/usargythemonk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SargyTheMonk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/31/02 1:21:24 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: In deference to the wheelchair bandit</span><hr size=1> Arleanna Wrote...<br>
